  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Reflect</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This project added a dimension that doesn't exist in smaller systems. Ask yourself:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Auto-scaling:</strong> What did it feel like to watch the ASG scale out during a load test? Was it faster or slower than you expected? Did the scaling policies trigger at the right thresholds?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Cost as a design constraint:</strong> Did you think about cost during the architecture phase? How did the cost estimate compare to the actual bill? Was the TV feature spike a surprise or something the architecture anticipated?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">The race condition:</strong> Was the stock consistency problem harder or easier than expected? Which locking approach did you choose and why? Would you choose differently next time?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Terraform modules:</strong> Did the modular structure help or feel like overhead? When you needed to change the CDN configuration, could you do it without touching the database module?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">ADRs:</strong> Were the ADRs useful during implementation? When you had to justify a decision to Emma (the cost report), did the ADR help frame the explanation?</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">"It works" vs "it works efficiently":</strong> The system worked before the TV feature. It still worked during the TV feature. But the cost spiked. What's the difference between a system that handles load and a system that handles load efficiently? Where does cost optimisation fit in the development process?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The "show someone" moment</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open two browser windows side by side. In one, your Grafana dashboard showing ASG instance count and request rate. In the other, the k6 terminal running a load test. Watch the metrics respond in real time:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>k6 ramps up to 100 users — request rate climbs on the dashboard</li>
    <li>CPU crosses 70% — ASG instance count increases from 2 to 4</li>
    <li>All requests succeed — no errors, no overselling</li>
    <li>k6 ramps down — request rate drops, CPU drops, ASG scales back to 2</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">"The system scales automatically under load and recovers when load drops. No manual intervention. No overselling. And I know what it costs."</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Key insight:</strong> Scaling isn't just a technical problem — it's a business problem. Emma's system needs to handle 10x traffic spikes without losing orders. But it also needs to not cost 10x permanently. Auto-scaling solves the first problem. Cost monitoring and scaling policy optimisation solve the second. The architecture serves both the user experience and the business economics.</p>
  </Callout>

